{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-8","id":"msg_01VdEysCknt9kwEuDYotjnVk","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Task complete and verified.\n\n## Summary\n\nThe Elasticsearch HTTP API is now reachable at `https://es.example.com` through ingress-nginx, with plain HTTP blocked.\n\n**What I found:**\n- The ES backend (`es-http` service, port 9200) speaks **HTTPS itself** (TLS-enabled X-Pack security) — plain HTTP to it fails, HTTPS returns a 401 auth challenge.\n- The `nginx` ingress class is provided by the controller in the `ingress-nginx` namespace.\n\n**What I did:**\n1. Generated a self-signed cert with SAN `DNS:es.example.com` and stored it as TLS secret `es-tls` in the `elasticsearch` namespace.\n2. Created Ingress `es-ingress` (`ingressClassName: nginx`) for host `es.example.com`, routing to `es-http:9200` with:\n   - `backend-protocol: HTTPS` — so nginx re-encrypts to the TLS-enabled ES backend (otherwise nginx would speak plaintext to a TLS port and fail).\n   - `force-ssl-redirect: \"true\"` — so plain HTTP does not reach the API.\n\n**Verification (tested against the controller ClusterIP with host resolution):**\n- `https://es.example.com/` → **401** (ES's own auth challenge — the request traversed ingress → backend successfully, served with the `CN=es.example.com` cert).\n- `http://es.example.com/` → **308** redirect; plain HTTP never reaches the backend.\n- All Elasticsearch pods (es-0/1/2, 3/3 statefulset) and the ingress controller remain Running/healthy.\n\nNo operators or CRDs were installed; only a TLS secret and a standard Ingress resource were added."}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":2,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1055,"cache_read_input_tokens":31489,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1055},"output_tokens":5,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management"